I found a wonderful girl for Bonfire. She told me that she used to see my horseprints in the dirt and tried to imagine what the horse looked like. Said it gave her the chills ... and of course I knew what that was like. Beauty was bought by the people who owned the barn where we keeping her, which was rright across the country road from our home there in the country . She was a little older of course and I really think she liked it where she was and was content to stay. Bonfire lived on the next farm down the road ... so it worked out.\r\x00b\x00\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xffT\x00\x00\x00\x80\x88:\x00\x00\x00\x81\x90\x18\x00\x00\x00A\xc0\x12\x00\x00\x00V\x00e\x00r\x00d\x00a\x00n\x00a\x00\x84\x90\x14\x00\x00\x00\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x00\x00\x00\xff\x8f \xda\x07c2\xa1\x88@\x02\x00\x00\xa8\xc06\x02\x00\x00\xac\x18\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x01\x00\xc9\x1c\x00\x14P\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04\x9b\t\x00\x00How long DID you have her, and how/when did you lose her. Dad had her vanned up to Leesburg from the log cabin ... we boarded her on a farm right on the township limits ... ( the farm is still there, I was amazed, untouched. Even the stone steps I used to use to go over the fence into her pasture! It was owned by a Farmer by the name of Kitts and he boarded the occasional horse and accepted money from the government for not planting corn. You gotta be a farmer to understand farm subsidies I guess. I kept Beauty there through that first winter and into the spring of 1959. She foaled a beautiful dark chestnut filly I named Bonfire on April 3rd, 1959. Strangely I always remember that babys birthday even now. I took the bus out to be with them for a most of that spring summer and fall. We had eventually moved to Alexandria Virginia and got the Duchess that fall. So I rode as much as I could but usually the only way I could get out there was to bus it. In the spring of 1960 Dad became interested in the countryside around Chantilly so he had Beauty and Bonfire vanned to\xa0 Boarding and training stable which was quite a bit closer and where he could drive me out to ride. I never had to bus it there and I am not sure I even could have. At the end of the summer when Mom and Dad split up and we moved to Bethesda Dad had the horses moved out to Mr. Kitts again because I knew the area and had riding partners out there. ( and I had figured out how to take the local buses to downtown Washington and then the greyhound again out to Leesburg. That lasted until we moved to Meadville in the Spring of 1961 and Dad again had the horses vanned to Pa ....... I was having a great time training Bonfire and she was really doing well, I was very proud of her. Then in about February Dad told me that we were going to be moving where the horses this time couldn\'t go ..... and that the best thing for me to do would be to find them a good home .... which I very professionally did. I cried a little but really I was alright with letting them go. It really wasn\'t a question .I knew that Dad would have taken them if he could have .... When he eventually told me we were going to Nassau I understood that they couldn\'t make the trip this time.\xa0 ( I stashed the cat I had gotten in Bethesda though in a beachbagt=.... wasn\'t leaving her behind. Have pictures of Heidi in Nassau ..... she is the cat Charles eventually took to San Francisco when I went to was I doing when Dr. Brown was visiting San Antonio .... being his escort, of course .... Which meant that he was met by a car ... thence to an airport for a charter flight to .... somewhere in New Mexico .... from there a more direct flight to San Antonio.\xa0 Hey, you asked .... I\'m telling .... but much will be left to your imagination. He was reviewing progress and had some ideas of his own .... which we spent the next week .... accomplishing. Same situation for the return .... I took the chance of being on his flight to Catalina .... going over in a co-pilots seat .... never actually got out ... but made sure that he was met by his family. Was relieved and disappointed that I never caught a glimpse of Linda .... Went prepared ... looking quite different. though film badges are interpreted to give a dose, they are not called dosimeters. Dosimeter is a specific nonclementure for a the thing that looks like a pen. The film badge and its holder is very thin and about 1" by 1" in size. I can see that they could be used as an ID thingy as well, but if you stuck anything to the front of them, then their beta sensitivity would drop. So yea, they werent around radioiosotpes, but X rays from high voltage equipment, cathode ray tubes . In my mind, a film badge and a dosimeter are two separate items. A dosimeter badge is beyond my ken. The same film badge can be worn for a period of more than one day, depending on the situation. The down side of the film badge is that they have to be sent off to a specialised facility which can develop the film and from the exposure on it due to ionising radiation, come up with a beta and a gamma and X ray exposure dose. Where I worked I think we wore the same badge for a week. It has helped me enormously with certain details of our story. In the summer of 1966 the experience that Linda Brown had with dosimeters was that both she and her Dad (and everyone working at the Decker Lab , at least "on top of the hill) were required to wear them and that they were part of an identity badge that was sewn in to each of their lab coats. She had assumed that the entire identity badge would have had to have been removed but now its obvious with your input that the "tube" part of the badge could be removed separately each evening. And then drawn from what you said it would have been recalibrated for the following day. The actual design of the tube now obviously allowed it to be "detached" from the " badge" which was noted in her journal as being " sewn into" the white lab coat. empirical and from reading, would be that in this science, the means of communications would have been established long before the ability to generate the means of travel. Therefore, I believe the method of communication was developed in principle and in practice between 1946 and 1953. Now, going out on a limb a little further, this advancement and knowledge would have opened doors as to solving obstacles to generate propulsion (it really isn\'t that but we\'ll use that word for now). The biggest obstacle was overcome in the late sixties and it was in Philadelphia ( it may have been started in Meadville but if I were Dr Brown, I wouldn\'t have even bothered, but then, I further believe that it was done to create a fork in the road and create a diversion from his real needs.) After Meadville, he needed to test a theory and prove a principle in a vacuum. I am rambling. When you walked in it was on the cold side with the interior all painted a flat black, very non-reflective but the paint was marked off in spots from use. It was a giant sphere that was wider than it was tall due to the fact that there was a walkway that proceeded from either side of the door that would permit walking around the entire inside of the sphere. From the walkway, you walk down ramps to the floor of the sphere, the ramps were probably at 30 degrees and put you about another 30 inches lower from the walkway. About 2/3 of the way up the sides were placed different light arrays. These could produce different wavelengths of light from the infrared to the ultraviolet. Supposedly they could do more but that is only what someone present mentioned( x-ray, gamma etc). There was a large window, approximately 3 feet by 3 feet, this was were the operator and/or observer could view the inside of the Tolstoys grandson and speaking so much in Russian. They had talked for a long time .... a conversation that started very ..... almost .... menacingly ... don\'t know how to say it other than that. It made me uncomfortable because I couldn\'t understand what they were saying but from their body language I could tell that it was not immediately a friendly thing. Dad sidled up to me at one point since we were just sitting there like bumps on logs and said .... lets go for a walk ..... by the time we got back the entire attitude had changed at that table, they were laughing and Tolstoy amazed me with this big belly laugh which I would never have expected from him.\xa0 When we left Morgan was just barely touching the ground ..... I asked him when I could what the problem was at the beginning and he just laughed and flashed that wonderful smile at me and just said ...."Oh .... Russians .... they can be a solomne and suspicious sort. Apparently Morgan had passed because the next day he and Dad were having an animated discussion about what David had just said .... that the secrets of the Universe are known by a begonia and they covered again the same information I had been told as a child. Only thing is .... a jet breaking the sound barrier. high voltage is involved \r\x00\x92\x00\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xffr\x00\x00\x00\x80\x88:\x00\x00\x00\x81\x90\x18\x00\x00\x00A\xc0\x12\x00\x00\x00V\x00e\x00r\x00d\x00a\x00n\x00a\x00\x84\x90\x14\x00\x00\x00\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x00\x00\x00\xff\x8f \xd9\x07c2\xa1\x88D\x00\x00\x00\xa8\xc0:\x00\x00\x00\xac\x18\x00\x00\xa3\x80\x1c\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x02\x00\xc9\x1c\x00\x14\xc8\x1c\x00\x1cP\x00\x00\x00\n\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01,\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x80&\x11\x00\x00\x05\x00\xad\x1c\x00\x08\t\x1d\x00\x14\x03\x1c\x00\x0c \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$M8\x033\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04\xa9\x03\x00\x00In my opinion, the anode is either the GE 100 engine or attached directly below. The exhaust then vents through the metal cathode (probably titanium/tungsten alloy to handle the heat) and the jet stream then carries the negative charges into the exhaust contrail. As a result, an exceedingly high potential difference (15 Million Volts) builds between the B2 and the air behind it. This is exactly as Townsend Brown envisioned in his patent. This high potential difference generates the plasma envelope around the aircraft necessary to attenuate radar. How much of the thrust necessary for flight is related to the Brown effect, I can only speculate. However, since the aircraft has an almost non-existent heat signature, I would expect the engines are only run at a low RPM once the potential difference is established. I have previously noticed a cooling effect in ion winds, so this may be involved in the heat signature reduction. \x80\x80Y\x12\x00\x00\x18\x10\x80\x80\xff\x10\x00\x80\x00\x00\xf8v\x0f\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\xc2L\x95\xa7e\xba\xa9E\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04\x89\x05\x00\x00I love the picture of Dad stepping off the Duchess. Note how cold it is .... March of 1960 ..... note the condition of the Duchess .... I had forgotten the timing .... so it was the Summer of 1959 .... that we spent the whole damn summer on her ... going from the old cruiser that she was ....peeling paint and varnish and all .... to what you see there.\xa0 So, for sure .... all the summer of 1959 we were in Alexandria ..... and through to the summer of 1960 .... then by fall of 1960 .... out of there. (thats when Mom and I moved to Bethesda .... and he went to Meadville. I can remember hearing her sob quietly when they thought I was asleep. " I just can\'t..... I just won\'t do it anymore" and all Daddy said was a sort of plaintive .... and resigned ...."Sweetie" ..... so we spent the fall by ourselves, Mother got a job ... we had steak on Fridays, girls night out ..... then the call came in where he had collapsed in Meadville and was in the hospital and she lit out of that Bethesda hospital only after she knew that Helen had cleared the door and would stay ...... now it makes alot more sense to me ...that Helen would be available like that to just "drop everything" and come to stay with me for three weeks .... In a couple of months we moved to Meadville for the summer .... and by the next spring we were in Nassau and well, you know the drill ...... and Mom and Dad never split up again .......ehd\r\x00\x00b\x00\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xffT\x00\x00\x00\x80\x88:\x00\x00\x00\x81\x90\x18\x00\x00\x00A\xc0\x12\x00\x00\x00V\x00e\x00r\x00d\x00a\x00n\x00a\x00\x84\x90\x14\x00\x00\x00\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x88\x0b\x00\xc8\x00\x00\x00\x0e\x00h\x12\x00\x00\xf0\x87\x0b\x000\x00\x00\x00\r\x00_\x12\x00\x00 \x87\x0b\x00\xd0\x00\x00\x00\x0e\x00i\x12\x00\x00\xf0\x86\x0b\x000\x00\x00\x00\r\x00\xff\x10\x00\x80 \x8f\x0b\x00\x00\x04\x00\x00\xc2L\x95\xa7e\xba\xa9E\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04W\x02\x00\x00It didn\'t really surprise me all that much when I discovered that Tom had hooked up with Mom and Dad again in Homestead and he was doing the same sort of stuff. The only change was that people in Homestead had nicknamed him " Key west Bill" and so that\'s what I started calling him too. I asked him which was his real name, Bill or Tom and he laughed and said both! Thomas William and I thought that was cool because I automatically thought of " Chip" Williams\xa0 ( Thomas Nottingham Williams\xa0III, still love that name, so snotty)\xa0 Anyway ..... lost track of him when we moved to Philadelphia.\xa0 ehd\r\x00\x00\xcc\x00\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xff\xa2\x00\x00\x00\x80\x88J\x00\x00\x00\x81\x90\x18\x00\x00\x00A\xc0\x12\x00\x00\x00V\x00e\x00r\x00d\x00a\x00n\x00a\x00\x84\x90$\x00\x00\x00\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x00\x00\x00\xff\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x00\x00\x00\xff\x8f \xd9\x07c2\xa1\x88\x84\x02\x00\x00\xa8\xc0Z\x02\x00\x00\xad\x90"\x00\x00\x00\xae(Q\x02\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\xae(\x03\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\xae(\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\xa3\x80\x1c\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x02\x00\xc9\x1c\x00\x14\xc8\x1c\x00\x1c`\x00\x00\x00\x14\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\xe2\x00\x00\x00\x00\xeb\x00\x00\x00\x01Q\x02\x00\x00\t\x00\x01\x00\x00\x80Z\x12\x00\x00\x05\x00\xad\x1c\x00\x08\t\x1d\x00\x14\x03\x1c\x00\x0c \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$T\x87N3\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x80[\x12\x00\x00\x05\x00\xad\x1c\x00\x08\t\x1d\x00\x14\x03\x1c\x00\x0c \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$T\x87N3\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04C\x02\x00\x00Anyway ..... " Tom" was what we called him when we had the Duchess on the Potomac river. He helped with the reconditioning of that boat ( she was really rough when we bought her in 1959. Stripped and redid her mahoghany deckhouse ..He slept there on the boat, . custom made some furniture for the aft cabin. He was a good guy, alot of fun. He used to take me bowling sometimes when we were in Alexandria but then the summer\xa0of 60 he shoved off on a grand adventure ... canoeing down the inland waterway to Florida. \xcd\x0b\x00\xc0\x00\x00\x00\x0e\x00\xb3\x12\x00\x00\xf8\xcc\x0b\x00(\x00\x00\x00\r\x00\xac\x12\x00\x008\xcc\x0b\x00\xc0\x00\x00\x00\x0e\x00\xb4\x12\x00\x00\x10\xcc\x0b\x00(\x00\x00\x00\r\x00\xff\x10\x00\x80\xd0\xdd\x0b\x00\x00\x08\x00\x00\xc2L\x95\xa7e\xba\xa9E\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04\x85\x05\x00\x00I love the picture of Dad stepping off the Duchess. Note how cold it is .... March of 1960 ..... note the condition of the Duchess .... I had forgotten the timing .... so it was the Summer of 1959 .... that we spent the whole damn summer on her ... going from the old cruiser that she was ....peeling paint and varnish and all .... to what you see there.\xa0 So, for sure .... all the summer of 1959 we were in Alexandria ..... and through to the summer of 1960 .... then by fall of 1960 .... out of there. (thats when Mom and I moved to Bethesda .... and he went to Meadville. I can remember hearing her sob quietly when they thought I was asleep. " I just can\'t..... I just won\'t do it anymore" and all Daddy said was a sort of plaintive .... and resigned ...."Sweetie" ..... so we spent the fall by ourselves, Mother got a job ... we had steak on Fridays, girls night out ..... then the call came in where he had collapsed in Meadville and was in the hospital and she lit out of that Bethesda hospital only after she knew that Helen had cleared the door and would stay ...... now it makes alot more sense to me ...that Helen would be available like that to just "drop everything" and come to stay with me for three weeks .... In a couple of months we moved to Meadville for the summer .... and by the next spring we were in Nassau and well, you know the drill ...... and Mom and Dad never split up again \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$\xc14n2\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x06\x00>\x1c\x00\x14\x84\x1c\x00\x14B\x1c\x00\x88\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\x01\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\t\x04\x03\x00\x00\x00\r\x00\x00\x9d\x00\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xff\x82\x00\x00\x00\x80\x88F\x00\x00\x00\x81\x90\x18\x00\x00\x00A\xc0\x12\x00\x00\x00V\x00e\x00r\x00d\x00a\x00n\x00a\x00\x84\x90\x14\x00\x00\x00\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$\xc04n2\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04U\t\x00\x00Dad went nearly immediately to the Vega plant in 1942 ... just weeks actually after leaving the Navy. My impression was that Mom already knew that they were moving before the departure from the Navy because she was all packed up. There are no records as to actually how long they stayed at the Laurel Canyon address. By December of 1945 (when I was born) , they had already moved to Laguna Beach. Mother moved by herself during the early spring of that year. Dad had been injured (Paul will tell you more, but it had to do with being in Germany at the end of the war. He was back in the states and recovering. Mother chose a house by the sea that had stairs to the beach. She would make him walk down the steps in the morning, he would stay all day ... she would serve lunch down there and then he would walk back up in the afternoon. I think her tough love and attention probably saved him . Anyway .... in 1947 (nov) we moved to Hawaii and lived so far back in the hills we needed that command car that was mentioned. Soon after we were set up there with a garden and plenty of canned goods Dad left us (Mom, Grandmother Brown, Joseph and me) and disappeared out of our lives until sometime in 1950. Then the Pearl Harbor demonstration .... onward then to Los Angeles, then Washington , Cleveland, Washington... again .... lets see ... that makes it 1953 ... then Zanesville Ohio for us (I don\'t know where for Dad) then back to Washington .... and Leesburg ..... Florida (Umatilla) in 1957, Walkertown N.C. in 1958 .... shared with Leesburg Va again .... then Alexandria Va..... Meadville Pa (1961) shared with Nassau ..... and in 1962 ... a few places I cant even remember and then Paoli Pa in the summer ...... and Ashlawn for 1963 and 1964. ...... Homestead Florida (remote lab) in 1965 ... 1966 Philadelphia and the Decker lab(Drake first and then the townhouse on Lombard) .... by 1967 we had been on the road for a couple of months shuttling between Odlums place in Indio and San Francisco but by summer we had settled at Santa Monica and were working at GTI. by the next year ....... well ....... I met my future husband and my path split from my parents .... anything after 1967 gets a little harder for me to trace because some of those years I was not with them. But it looks like you have a pretty good idea. Sort of. Now you can see why Paul buries his head in the sand! When electrically energized to the limit ...(just under the electrical breakdown ), high density plasma is generated in the region immediately adjacent to the incandescent cathode where the electric field density is greatest. By highly effective electro-striction, due to the unique geometry of the field, the plasma is accelerated toward all portions of the concave anodic surface creating pressure against said surface. It is within this region extending outward toward the periphery of the anode that the plasma receives its principal acceleration. It is then driven beyond the rim and flows with high velocity .... in a circuit back to the cathode ... the flow pattern takes the form of a torodial vortex."\r\x00\x00\xa2\x00\x00\x00\xff\xff\xff\xff\x94\x00\x00\x00\x80\x88P\x00\x00\x00\x81\x90\x18\x00\x00\x00A\xc0\x12\x00\x00\x00V\x00e\x00r\x00d\x00a\x00n\x00a\x00\x84\x90*\x00\x00\x00\x94\x88\x0e\x00\x00\x00@\x18\x00\x00F \x00\x00\x00\xff\x94\x88\x14\x00\x00\x00\x00\x08@\x18\x00\x00F \x00\x00\x00\xffH\x18\xbc\x02\x8f \xda\x07c2\xa1\x88D\x05\x00\x00\xa8\xc0\x10\x05\x00\x00\xad\x90,\x00\x00\x00\xae(D\x02\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\xae((\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\xae(g\x02\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\xae(8\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x01\x00\xc9\x1c\x00\x14f\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x80b\x13\x00\x00\x05\x00\xad\x1c\x00\x08\t\x1d\x00\x14\x03\x1c\x00\x0c \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$l\xb5\x914\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x80c\x13\x00\x00\x05\x00\xad\x1c\x00\x08\t\x1d\x00\x14\x03\x1c\x00\x0c \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$l\xb5\x914\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04\x85\x01\x00\x00Last time that I will quote your own stuff back to you, MAYBE. Mom and Dad thought I was asleep belowdecks I am sure but I woke to the sound of Mother quietly crying. I heard.."I just can\'t do this anymore! I just won\'t do this anymore. And Daddys voice came across as pained too.... All he said was .... " Sweetie Did I use that already in a chapter some where, or in a message to you?? Do you recall? I\'m going to have to find that reference, too.I remember that he wrote that to you. I have seen it. When I read that I automatically and immediately thought of the badge that I saw him flash. National Reconnaisance Office. Strangely it looked a little familiar because the Whitehall Rand stationary that Dad had made up that year had the earth like that with a satellite circling it. I wish to God I could find some of that old stationary, My thought is now that it would be nearly identical to what was later adopted for the NRO. Andrew seems to remember seeing that letterhead too so maybe someday we will find an old letter or someone will volunteer a copy from something that Dad sent also had my horses moved out to McClean which was closer .... and he would take me out and wait while I rode.... for that summer anyway.\xa0 When Mom and I moved to Bethesda I moved the horses back out to Mr. Kitts ... the farmer in Leesburg and continued my commuting to ride on the weekends. back on the bus!\xa0 \x1c\x00$\x1f\x1c\x00$\xc7\xac\x914\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x01\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x80\x03\x00\xfe\x1c\x00\x10@\x1c\x00\x1c#\x1c\x00\x1c\t\x04\x8b\x05\x00\x00The move up from North Carolina to Alexandria\xa0( eventually ... Wirt Street in Leesburg first) was accompanied by some digree of financing. I can remember that Mother and I were able to shop for nice things, she enrolled me in a dance class , bought some saddlery for my horses and some riding clothes .... Dad bought the Cadillac in the summer of 1960... and of course we already had the Duchess ... he bought whole suites of furniture for the apartment and as I recall when Joseph visited between classes in Oregon ... he bought him an Impala convertible that was next to new, if not new. So there was money coming from somewhere and on a regular basis. I was naturally careful with money and never asked for something that I didn\'t really need ... but I remember distinctly being at Stombachs Saddlery in George town and mentioning that I needed ( someday, too much to wish for in one whole moment) an English saddle and bridle for my young Bonfire.....she was too young that summer to ride but I wanted something light to put on her back and I was being very meticulous about keeping notes of my training and her responses . Dad agreed that I needed those things ...and bought them for me right off the bat ... a Saddle from Stombachs! You just have no idea how much that meant to me at the time! I had been in there time and time again when we lived out at Montressor. Pipe dreams having a saddle from Stombachs.
